    <text>
        <front>
            <div type="summary">
                <p>
                    A letter from the Hogarth Press to the Ship Binding Works regarding stock
                </p>
            </div>
        </front>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName>Not Specified</placeName>
                        <date when="1930-09-17">17 September, 1930</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>
                          Messrs. <orgName>R. &#38; R. Clark Lit.</orgName>
                        </addrLine>
                        <addrLine>
                          Brandon Street
                        </addrLine>
                        <addrLine>
                          Edinburgh
                        </addrLine>
                    </address>
                    <salute>
                        Dear Sirs,
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <title>THE EDWARDIANS</title> - Third Impression.<lb/>
                    We shall be glad if you will print a third impression, 3000,<lb/>
                    of the above book, and despatch to the <orgName>Ship Binding Works</orgName> as soon<lb/>
                    as possible as the matter is urgent. <persName>Messrs. Spalding &#38; Hodge</persName> are<lb/>
                    delivering to you tomorrow, or Friday, 33 reams of <orgName>Kingsway Ant. Ld.<lb/>
                    Cr. Svo.</orgName> paper, which we believe to be sufficient to print 3000 copies.<lb/>
                    Kindly note to alter SECOND IMPRESSION to THIRD IMPRESSION on the<lb/>
                    title page, and on the back of the title page/ add 'third impression'<lb/>
                    <date when="1930-10">October 1930</date>, in italics. We shall re quire 2750 jackets only as<lb/>
                    our binders hold a balance of about 300. Please let us know the<lb/>
                    earlierst date when you will be able to deliver to our binders, so<lb/>
                    as to enable us to get some idea when we are likely to have the bound<lb/>
                    copies delivered at the Press.<lb/>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        Yours faithfully,
                    </salute>
                    <signed>
                      <orgName>The Hogarth Press</orgName><lb/>
                      <unclear reason="faded">Autograph</unclear><note>This is most likely the autograph of Peggy Belsher, who was a secretary at the Press from 1928 to 1936, as the barely legible signature seems to overlap with her name and the time period.</note><lb/>
                      Secretary<lb/>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
